# 🧠 Cerebral Cortex

> The cerebral cortex is the **outermost 2–4 mm mantle of the cerebrum**, comprising ~16 billion neurons organized into six distinct horizontal layers (neocortex) and functional vertical columns, forming the anatomical substrate for perception, movement, language, cognition, and consciousness.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Brain]] — outermost structure of the cerebrum; gray matter surface
- [[Motor Pathway]] — layer V Betz cells → corticospinal tract; area 4 primary motor cortex
- [[Somatosensory System]] — areas 3a/3b/1/2 postcentral gyrus; thalamic VPL/VPM input to layer IV
- [[Visual System]] — area 17 (V1), striate cortex; optic radiation → layer IV
- [[Language and Speech]] — Broca's area (44/45), Wernicke's area (22); dominant hemisphere
- [[Prefrontal Cortex]] — areas 9/10/11/46 anterior frontal lobe; executive function
- [[Thalamus]] — specific relay nuclei → layer IV; corticothalamic feedback from layer VI
- [[Basal Ganglia]] — receives cortical input (layer V/VI → striatum); motor loop output back via thalamus
- [[Cerebellum]] — cortico-ponto-cerebellar pathway; receives processed motor cortex output

## 🗂️ Key Information
| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Thickness | 2–4 mm (varies by region: primary sensory cortex thinner, motor cortex thicker) |
| Total surface area | ~2,500 cm² (most folded into sulci); ~1/3 exposed on gyral crowns |
| Neuron number | ~16–20 billion cortical neurons |
| Gray matter | Cortex = gray matter (cell bodies, dendrites, axons, synapses, glia) |
| White matter | Subcortical myelinated axons (association, commissural, projection fibers) |
| Cortical types | Neocortex (6 layers, 90% of cortex); allocortex (3 layers: paleocortex/piriform, archicortex/hippocampus) |
| Specialization | Primary cortices (sensory/motor); unimodal association; heteromodal association (polymodal) |
| Hemispheric dominance | Left: language (95% right-handers, 70% left-handers); Right: visuospatial, prosody, attention |
| Blood supply | MCA (lateral surface); ACA (medial/parasagittal); PCA (occipital, inferior temporal) |

