## 🔑 Cortical Layers (Neocortex) — Layer-by-Layer

| Layer | Name | Thickness | Main Cell Types | Inputs | Outputs | Special Features |
|-------|------|-----------|-----------------|--------|---------|-----------------|
| **I** | Molecular (plexiform) | Thin | Sparse: Cajal-Retzius cells (fetal); mainly dendrites + horizontal axons | Nonspecific thalamic (diffuse) | None (no projection neurons) | Site of apical dendritic tufts of deeper pyramidal cells; inhibitory interneurons |
| **II** | External granular | Thin | Small stellate (granule) cells; small pyramidal cells | Corticocortical (ipsilateral + contralateral) | Short corticocortical output | Receives ipsilateral association fibers |
| **III** | External pyramidal | Moderate | Medium pyramidal cells; increasing size toward III base | Corticocortical (layer II/III of other areas) | **Corticocortical output** (association to ipsilateral cortex + commissural via corpus callosum) | Dominant layer for long-range cortical communication |
| **IV** | Internal granular | Variable | **Stellate (spiny granule) cells**; small pyramidal | **Specific thalamic relay nuclei** (main thalamic input layer) | Short corticocortical to layers II/III/V | **Thickest in primary sensory cortex (koniocortex)**; **absent in primary motor cortex (agranular)** |
| **V** | Internal pyramidal | Thick | **Large pyramidal cells** (Betz cells in M1); varied sizes | Corticocortical; nonspecific thalamic | **Subcortical projection output**: corticospinal, corticobulbar, corticopontine, corticostriatal, cortical to superior colliculus | **Thickest layer in primary motor cortex**; Betz cells largest neurons in CNS (~100 μm) |
| **VI** | Multiform (fusiform) | Thick | Polymorphic/fusiform cells; mixed | Corticocortical (layers II–V) | **Corticothalamic feedback** (layer VI → thalamic relay nucleus); some subcortical | Modulates thalamic gain; feedback control |

### Key Layer Rules
- **Inputs arrive mainly at layer IV** (specific thalamic) and layer I (nonspecific)
- **Outputs leave mainly from layer III** (to cortex) and **layer V** (to brainstem/spinal cord) and **layer VI** (back to thalamus)
- **Koniocortex** (dust cortex) = thick layer IV = primary sensory areas (V1, A1, S1)
- **Agranular cortex** = absent or thin layer IV = primary motor cortex (M1, area 4)

