## 🔑 Cortical Columns (Mountcastle Units)

| Property | Detail |
|----------|--------|
| Discoverer | Vernon Mountcastle (1957) — cat somatosensory cortex |
| Size | ~300–500 μm diameter; 6 layers deep |
| Definition | **Vertical functional unit**: all neurons in a column respond to the same peripheral stimulus (same modality, same receptive field location) |
| Organization | Neurons arranged in minicolumns (~80 neurons, 40–50 μm wide) → macrocolumns (~300–500 μm) → modules (e.g., V1 ocular dominance columns, orientation columns, blobs) |
| Examples | V1: **orientation columns** (neurons prefer same stimulus orientation); **ocular dominance columns** (L vs R eye input); **blob regions** (cytochrome oxidase blobs, color-selective); S1: digit-specific columns; M1: muscle-specific columns |
| Significance | Functional unit of cortical computation; information processing is columnar, not just laminar |

