## 🔑 Cortical Fiber Systems

### Intrahemispheric (Association) Fibers
| Fiber Bundle | Connects | Function |
|-------------|----------|----------|
| **Arcuate fasciculus / SLF-III** | Broca's area (44/45) ↔ Wernicke's area (22) | Language (phonological loop); lesion → conduction aphasia |
| **Uncinate fasciculus** | Orbital frontal cortex ↔ anterior temporal lobe | Emotional-behavioral regulation; damaged in temporal lobe lesions |
| **Cingulum** | Cingulate cortex ↔ parahippocampal gyrus | Limbic circuit; memory; emotional processing |
| **Superior longitudinal fasciculus (SLF)** | Frontal ↔ parietal ↔ temporal ↔ occipital | Multimodal integration; spatial attention |
| **Inferior longitudinal fasciculus (ILF)** | Occipital ↔ temporal (fusiform) | Object recognition; face processing |
| **Superior fronto-occipital fasciculus** | Frontal ↔ occipital | Visual attention; neglect |

### Commissural Fibers (Interhemispheric)
| Structure | Connects | Function/Clinical |
|-----------|----------|-------------------|
| **Corpus callosum — genu** | Prefrontal cortex (bilateral) | Executive coordination; alien hand syndrome (anterior CC lesion) |
| **Corpus callosum — body** | Parietal cortex (bilateral); somatosensory | Interhemispheric somatosensory transfer |
| **Corpus callosum — splenium** | Occipital + posterior temporal (bilateral) | Visual information sharing; splenium lesion → alexia without agraphia (left visual cortex + splenium disconnection) |
| **Anterior commissure** | Temporal poles (bilateral) + olfactory tracts | Olfactory and temporal lobe connections; small; crosses in lamina terminalis |
| **Fornix** | Hippocampus (bilateral) → mammillary bodies | Memory circuit; not strictly commissural but interhemispheric hippocampal |

### Split-Brain Studies (Sperry, Nobel 1981)
- Complete corpus callosotomy for intractable epilepsy → two cerebral hemispheres operating independently
- Left hemisphere: **dominant for language** (verbal report, reading, writing, arithmetic)
- Right hemisphere: **dominant for visuospatial** processing, holistic face recognition, drawing, music
- Right hemisphere: **mute** but can point, draw, and demonstrate understanding nonverbally
- **Clinical test**: flash image to left visual field (right hemisphere only) → patient cannot verbally name it but can point to or pick up object with left hand

