## 🏥 Clinical Significance

| Lesion/Condition | Location | Deficits | Key Features |
|-----------------|----------|----------|--------------|
| **Broca's aphasia** | Area 44/45 + surrounding frontal operculum (dominant) | Non-fluent, effortful speech; agrammatism; **comprehension relatively preserved** | "Telegraphic" speech; frustration; lesion usually includes white matter + Broca's area |
| **Wernicke's aphasia** | Area 22, posterior STG (dominant) | Fluent but **paraphasic** speech; **comprehension impaired**; unaware of errors; neologisms | Jargon aphasia; pure word deafness if primary auditory cortex spared |
| **Conduction aphasia** | Arcuate fasciculus / supramarginal gyrus (area 40) | Fluent speech; good comprehension; **poor repetition** | Phonemic paraphasias; can understand and initiate but cannot repeat |
| **Gerstmann's syndrome** | Angular gyrus (area 39), dominant left hemisphere | Tetrad: **acalculia + agraphia + finger agnosia + left-right disorientation** | Dominant parietal lobe; often with alexia |
| **Contralateral neglect** | Right parietal lobe (area 7, inferior parietal lobule) | Ignores contralateral (left) hemispace; doesn't dress left side; line bisection error | Right hemisphere dominant for attention; left neglect >> right neglect |
| **Alien hand syndrome** | Anterior corpus callosum + medial frontal (SMA) | One hand acts involuntarily, "alien" to the patient | Callosal: hands work at cross-purposes; frontal: involuntary grasping/utilization |
| **Agenesis of corpus callosum** | CC absent or partial (developmental) | Often **asymptomatic** (if isolated, congenital); split-brain syndrome only if acquired in adult | May have high-riding 3rd ventricle on MRI; associated with other malformations (e.g., Dandy-Walker) |
| **Focal cortical dysplasia** | Focal area of disorganized cortex | **Focal onset epilepsy** (often drug-resistant) | Type IIb: balloon cells + dysmorphic neurons; often MRI-negative; stereoEEG + surgical resection |
| **Cortical spreading depression** | Migraine cortex | Slow wave of depolarization + suppression spreading at 3–5 mm/min | Underlies migraine aura; visual aura (V1) most common; may also underlie stroke penumbra injury |
| **Hemispherectomy** | Entire hemisphere (usually pediatric) | Contralateral hemiplegia, hemianopia | Done for Rasmussen's encephalitis, large hemisphere malformations; excellent seizure outcomes; remarkable behavioral recovery in young children |

